gRPC vs. WebSockets — choosing the right bi-directional/server-push protocol
gRPC vs. WebSockets — choosing the right bi-directional/server-push protocol Nikola Sobadjiev · Follow 8 min
read · Mar 5, 2024 -- Listen Share
If you’re working on a project that requires bi-directional communication between clients and servers, you
might be facing a choice between WebSockets and a HTTP2-based solution like gRPC.
This article will give you a a list of pros and cons to each of them and hopefully make it easier for you to
make an informed decision.
Problem definition
For many projects, the default protocol of choice for client-server communication follows a request/response
pattern, often using HTTP. This assumes that a client requests data and a server responds to that request. The
problem arises whenever a server wants to proactively “notify” a client of a change, which happens more and
more with modern applications. More trivial solutions (like polling) aside, a solution to this problem
involved a more complicated communication medium, or a protocol that allows a server to maintain a persistant
connection with its clients. Here, the two more prominent options are the ones in the title — WebSockets and
gRPC.
Some derivative solutions
There are also some solutions that I’m not mentioning. For instance, a lot of people choose to achieve server
side push by using technologies, such as socket.io. Whereas it’s a perfectly viable option, it’s still a
solution based largely on WebSockets.
The opposite is true for gRPC. gRPC derives from HTTP2 and from Protobuf (which is the underlying
specification for the data transmitted). Sure, HTTP2 is the actual protocol that allows a server to push data
to a client. However, this protocol gets very complicated very quickly and I found it to be more practical to
use gPRC, which does the heavy lifting and is way more approachable.
A true alternative to WebSockets and gPRC in some cases can be long polling. Nevertheless, in this article, I
will be focusing on true bi-directional streaming.
TL;DR Which one should I choose?
If you want it quick and dirty, just use WebSockets.
Also if you’re running a service behind an LB, API Gateway, proxy or firewall that doesn’t support HTTP2, use
WebSockets.
If you like Protobuf, or you’re looking for a more explicit and less error prone way of defining your API, and
are willing to invest a couple of days to set it up, check out gRPC.
